    "summary": "Herod the Great (reigned 37–4 BC) was the Roman client king of Judea whose brilliant but brutal reign saw extraordinary construction projects — including the massive renovation of the [[event:1150|Second Temple of Jerusalem]] — alongside political murders that included members of his own family, creating a complex historical figure remembered alternately as a great builder and a tyrant.\n\nHerod was of Idumean (Edomite) descent, making his Jewish identity contested in the eyes of traditional Jews. He owed his throne to Roman backing, having supported first Antony and then Augustus after the [[event:1082|Battle of Actium]]. His construction projects were magnificent: Caesarea Maritima, a new port city with a deep harbor built from scratch; the Herodium, an artificial mountain-palace; Masada, a desert fortress-palace; and above all the complete rebuilding of the Jerusalem Temple on a platform so massive that portions still stand as the Western Wall. He was simultaneously paranoid and murderous: he had his Hasmonean wife Mariamne and her sons executed on suspicion of conspiracy. The massacre of the innocents in Matthew's Gospel, while not independently attested, reflects his historical reputation for murderous political calculation. He died in 4 BC, shortly after the birth ascribed to Jesus in that gospel.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herod_the_Great",
